    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>'Execution Duty'</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Maria Hrabowski letter says those who support death penalty ought to be called to 'execution duty' in same way citizens must serve on juries (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Inside the Death House,'' by Bob Herbert (column, Oct. 9):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Inside the Death House,'' by Bob Herbert (column, Oct. 9):</p>
        <p>Maybe every citizen, or at least those who support the death penalty, should be called to ''execution duty'' (for instance, to tie the legs or arms of the condemned) in the same way that citizens are asked to perform jury duty.</p>
        <p>Maybe before handling a death-penalty case, jurors should be required to witness a few executions. Maybe, just maybe, we would better understand what are we doing when we vote for politicians who support the death penalty.</p>
        <p>MARIA HRABOWSKI  Norwood, Mass., Oct. 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
